WLC uses the ports listed in the answers for these purposes:

	-&nbsp;Service port: For out-of-band management.&nbsp;

	-&nbsp;Distribution system port: To forward user data to/from the WLC and the switched network.

	-&nbsp;Console port: For out-of-band management.&nbsp;

	-&nbsp;Redundancy port: To communicate between two WLCs that cooperate to create a high-availability WLC cluster.&nbsp;

In this scenario, because of the recent boot, host B begins with an empty ARP table. As a result, host B needs to send an ARP request, also called an ARP broadcast, as the first frame. So this question asks about the flow of the ARP Request, which is a LAN broadcast, with a destination MAC address of FFFF.FFFF.FFFF. After receiving an ARP Reply from PC2, PC1 can send the ICMP Echo Request per the ping command to PC2 - a message PC1 encapsulates in a frame destined to PC2&#39;s MAC address.&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Considering each answer, beginning with the correct answers:


	The answer that claims the frame will be forwarded to host D is correct, in that the frame - a LAN broadcast - will be forwarded to all the hosts, including host D.
	The answer that claims that SW2 WILL&nbsp;forward the frame out SW2&#39;s G0/1 interface is correct for the LAN broadcast used for the ARP Request, as explained earlier.&nbsp;


Incorrect:


	The frame will be forwarded into SW1, then to SW2, and then to SW3, which rules out one incorrect answer that claims that the frame would not be forwarded to SW3.
	The answer that claims the frame will NOT be forwarded to host A is incorrect, because the frame - a LAN broadcast - will be forwarded to all the hosts, including host A.

This scenario focuses on switch learning. First, for switch learning, the switch&#39;s MAC address table may have some MAC addresses in it, but it does not contain the source MAC address of the frame. Switch learning means that the switch learns the source MAC address of the frame (identifying the one correct answer). Switches do not learn based on the destination MAC address of the frame (ruling out two answers).

	&nbsp;

	One incorrect answer mentions a frame loop. The frame does not contain any fields that allow a check to discover if the frame has been looping through the switch.

First, consider the three cases. On port G1/0/1, the PC has power, and a cable exists. As a result, the link works, and then autonegotiation works. However, on the other two links, a problem exists, so the link does not work. On G1/0/2, no cable exists, and on G1/0/3, the PC has no power. So, those links do not work, so no autonegotiation occurs.

Second, you must recall that the default settings for speed and duplex on switch interfaces cause them to use autonegotiation. As a result, the show interfaces status command, for interfaces in a down/down (notconnect) state, lists a status as if autonegotiation is yet to be done, using the word &quot;auto&quot; in each case. So, the output for G1/0/2 and G1/0/3 lists the speed and duplex as &quot;auto.&quot; 

For the working interface, G1/0/1, the output lists &quot;a-1000&quot; for the speed, meaning it autonegotiated to use 1000 Mbps. Similarly, the output shows &quot;a-full&quot; in the duplex heading, meaning it autonegotiated to use full duplex.

Three answers suggest values under the speed column for two interfaces. Two interfaces will list a speed value of &quot;auto&quot; (interfaces G1/0/2 and G1/0/3), making that answer correct. Three answers suggest values under the duplex column for exactly one interface. The answer listing &quot;a-full&quot; is correct, as interface G1/0/1 completes autonegotiation and chooses full duplex.
&nbsp;

As configured, SW2 will use a speed of 1000 and full duplex and will not send auto-negotiation messages. As a result, you need to think about how SW1 will behave, which is the essence of the question.

Switch SW1 uses IEEE parallel detection rules to detect the speed to use on the link, even with autonegotiation disabled on the SW2 end&nbsp;of the link. As a result, SW1 also uses 1000 Mbps (that is, 1 Gigabit/second). The IEEE parallel detection rules then state that to choose the duplex setting, use a default value based on the speed used. Those rules state that when running at 1 Gbps, to use full duplex. As a result, the link will come up because both switches use the same speed, and they will both use full duplex.&nbsp;

The three incorrect answers show a variety of incorrect combinations versus what actually happens.

&nbsp;

When the autonegotiation of both speed and duplex happens, two rules are followed:


		The two devices use the fastest speed supported by both devices

		The two devices use the best duplex setting, which is full duplex


	In this case, host B is shown as having a 10/100 NIC, with the switch using 10/100/1000 ports. As a result, both use 100 Mbps and both use full duplex.

	&nbsp;

	&nbsp;

The repeated show interfaces switchport commands in the exhibit all list an administrative mode. This mode matches the configuration setting on the switchport mode&nbsp;interface subcommand.&nbsp;

Any switch port with either trunk or dynamic desirable configured will trunk with a neighboring switch that uses trunk, dynamic desirable, or dynamic auto. To find the links that will trunk, find those whose configured setting per the switchport mode&nbsp;subcommand matches those combinations on the opposite ends of the link.

&nbsp;


	Of the correct answers, SW1&#39;s fa 0/2 uses a default configuration setting of dynamic auto. On the other end, SW2&#39;s fa0/1 interface is shown to have an administrative setting of trunk so that&nbsp;this link will trunk.&nbsp;
	The exhibit reveals that SW4&rsquo;s fa0/2 has been configured with an administrative mode of&nbsp;access, so the link between SW4 and SW2 does not trunk, making that answer correct.


&nbsp;

For the two incorrect answers:

&nbsp;


	SW3&rsquo;s interface fa0/1, once configured with the switchport mode dynamic auto command, will not trunk. The neighboring switch port, SW1&#39;s F0/3 port, also uses dynamic auto, which means both switches wait for the other to negotiate trunking.
	Finally, the link between SW1 and SW4 does not trunk because SW4&#39;s&nbsp;output lists the interface as administratively set to access mode. The answer claims the link operates as a trunk, making it incorrect.

Three answers list the trunking settings for the other switch; only one of these answers could possibly be correct. Because the exhibit shows the local switch with a trunking administrative mode set to dynamic auto,&nbsp;the local switch passively waits on the other switch to initiate trunk negotiations. Therefore, the other switch must have the setting of&nbsp; dynamic desirable, or it must be configured with trunking turned on (mode trunk).&nbsp;

	&nbsp;

	That same output identifies VLAN 3 as the native VLAN. Another of the correct answers states that VLAN 3 traffic will not have an 802.1Q header when crossing this trunk, which is the definition of a native VLAN.

	&nbsp;

	Finally, the third answer displays which VLANs whose traffic is allowed to cross the trunk. The output lists the allowed VLAN list, which does not include these two VLANs (900 and 901).

A switch port stops attempting to use Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) to negotiate trunking in two cases (matching the two correct answers.) The configuration can disable DTP using the switchport nonegotiate subcommand. Additionally, setting the administrative trunking mode to access, using the switchport mode access subcommand, also disables DTP.

	One incorrect answer lists the command switchport mode dynamic desirable. This command tells the switch to negotiate whether to use trunking and to initiate the negotiation process.

	The other incorrect answer lists a valid command, switchport access vlan 10.&nbsp;This command defines the access VLAN as VLAN 10, which is used if the port becomes an access port, but it does not define any rules about whether the port trunks or not and does not effect the trunk negotiation process.&nbsp;

The root election is still based on the lowest bridge ID. With default priority values, the switch that has the lowest MAC address&mdash;SW1&mdash;wins. SW2&rsquo;s fa0/1, SW3&rsquo;s fa0/1, and SW4&rsquo;s fa0/1 all receive a zero-cost BPDU from SW1, and each of these ports becomes the root port on its respective switches.

	&nbsp;

	When SW2 receives the zero-cost Hello from SW1 (root), it forwards the Hellos, after adding SW2&rsquo;s fa0/1 interface STP port cost to the original received cost. SW2&rsquo;s forwarded Hellos will have a cost of 1. SW3 will forward a Hello onto the trunk between itself and SW2, out SW3&rsquo;s fa0/2 interface, based on SW3&rsquo;s default fa0/1 port cost of 19. SW2 is advertising the lowest-cost Hello onto the trunk between itself and SW3, so SW2&rsquo;s fa0/3 becomes the designated port on that segment.

With all default settings related to STP costs, a Cisco IOS switch uses a port cost of 19 on ports running at 100-Mbps. Note that the cost could be configured statically. Additionally, the port cost defaults could be updated per the 802.1D 2004 standard. That said, as described in the question stem, all ports will have a cost of 19.

	In the Hello SW2 would send, SW2 would advertise its own root cost. SW2 calculates its root cost as the sum of the root cost in the BPDU it received on its root port (38), plus the cost of associated with that interface (19), for a total of 57.

	&nbsp;

The alternate port role acts as an alternate root port, while the backup port role serves as a backup designated port for a designated port on the same switch.

	First, for the answers that mention &ldquo;backup port,&rdquo; note that for a port to act as backup port, it must back up a designated port on that same switch. Also, that backup port must connect to the same collision domain. The collision domains include all the point-to-point links between switches and the links connected to the one LAN hub. Based on these facts, neither SW3 nor SW2 can have a backup port, because each does not connect with two ports to the same collision domain. However, switch SW4 does connect with two ports to the same collision domain (as created by the hub), so SW4 could use port F0/2 as an RSTP backup port.

	For the alternate port concept, each nonroot switch can have an alternate (root) port. The alternate cannot also be serving in the designated port role or already be serving in the root port role. Based on those rules, SW3&#39;s F0/4 and SW4&#39;s G0/1 could both be the alternate port. (SW2&rsquo;s port G0/2 could be an alternate port as well, but it is not listed as an answer.)&nbsp;

&nbsp;

	Cisco Catalyst switches support both the Cisco proprietary Port Aggregation Protocol (PAgP) and the IEEE standard protocol Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP). The desirable and auto keywords configure the switch to use PAgP, and the passive and active keywords configure the switch to use LACP. The&nbsp;on&nbsp;keyword enables the EtherChannel without using either of the protocols.

